  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, Department of the Interior contract obligations total $3.8B across 17,525 awards with an average award size of $215K. Obligations fell 42.2% year over year; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). The department has shifted from a multi-year peak of $8.1B in FY24 to $6.5B in FY25 and now to $3.8B in FY26. Spending in FY26 is concentrated in construction and IT services: the largest NAICS category is Water and Sewer Line and Related Structures Construction at $522M, followed by Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction at $380M and Computer Systems Design Services at $327M. Top vendors are a mix of large IT contractors and construction firms, led by GENERAL DYNAMICS INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY, INC. at $133M and AMES FEDERAL CONTRACTING GROUP LLC at $132M. The portfolio shows continued reliance on construction, civil engineering, and information technology services while award volume remains high and average award size remains moderate.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "What changed in Interior contract spending?",
        "body": "Total obligations are $3.8B in FY26 to date, down 42.2% year over year. The department moved from $8.1B in FY24 and $6.5B in FY25 to $3.8B in FY26, reflecting a smaller current-year obligation total. Award volume remains elevated at 17,525 awards, keeping the average award size at $215K."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Where is Interior spending concentrated?",
        "body": "Spending is concentrated in construction and IT categories: Water and Sewer Line and Related Structures Construction is $522M, Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction is $380M, and Computer Systems Design Services is $327M. Major contractors span IT and construction, with GENERAL DYNAMICS INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY, INC. at $133M and AMES FEDERAL CONTRACTING GROUP LLC at $132M among the top recipients."
      }
